th an Emphasis on Reinfried von Braunschweig -- tMiracles and Magic: Necromantic Practices Found in Cantiga 125 -- tMagic at the Margins: The Mystification of Maugis d’Aigremont -- tThe Magician at Home with his Family: Comparative Historical Ethnographies of Two Pre- Modern Magicians from Autobiographical Sources: John of Morigny and the Tibetan Monk Milarepa -- tCurious Clerks: Image Magic and Chaucerian Poetics -- tRepresenting Magic and Science in The Franklin’s Tale and The Canon’s Yeoman’s Tale: Chaucer’s Exploration of Connected Topics -- tMagic in Late Medieval German Literature: The Case of the Good Magician Malagis -- tMotives, Means, and a Malevolent Mantel: The Case of Morgan le Fay’s Transgressions in Sir Thomas Malory’s Le Morte Darthur -- tWitchcraft, Heinrich Kramer’s Nuremburg Handbook, and Ecclesiasticus: The Construction of the Fifteenth-Century Civic Sorceress -- tMagic and Ritual in Late-Medieval and Early-Modern Popular Medicine -- tAttempted Murder by Magic: The Sorcerer and His Apprentice in Marguerite de Navarre’s Heptaméron 1 -- tHow Magical Was Renaissance Magic? -- tMagic in Jacob Cornelisz van Oostsanen’s Saul and the Witch of Endor -- tHeterochronic Representation of Magic in Czech Chapbooks -- tRethinking Max Weber’s Theory of Disenchantment -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere are no clear demarcation lines between magic, astrology, necromancy, medicine, and even sciences in the pre-modern world. Under the umbrella term 'magic,' the contributors to this volume examine a wide range of texts, both literary and religious, both medical and philosophical, in which the topic is discussed from many different perspectives. The fundamental concerns address issue such as how people perceived magic, whether they accepted it and utilized it for their own purposes, and what impact magic might have had on the mental structures of that time. While some papers examine the specific appearance of magicians in literary texts, others analyze the practical application of magic in medical contexts. In addition, this volume includes studies that deal with the rise of the witch craze in the late fifteenth century and then also investigate whether the Weberian notion of disenchantment pertaining to the modern world can be maintained. Magic is, oddly but significantly, still around us and exerts its influence. Focusing on magic in the medieval world thus helps us to shed light on human culture at large.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aMagicxHistory. 0aMagicians. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aAyanna, Amiri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAzuela, Cristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenati, Chiara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerthelot, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClason, Christopher R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClassen, Albrecht, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClassen, Albrecht, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCoudert, Allison P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFanger, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalle, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGolan, Nurit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJarchow, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoten, Jiří, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMenaldi, Veronica, econtributor.4ctb4https